\begin_layout Subsubsection
Reuse - Materialization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reuse and materialization of data science artifacts refers to the ability
 to use existing artifacts, such as data, code, models, and results, in
 new data science projects and workflows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Artifacts reuse is desirable because it can save time and effort by avoiding
 the need to recreate existing artifacts from scratch.
 It also allows for easier collaboration and sharing of resources within
 an organization.
 However, in practice, data science artifacts are often not reusable due
 to several reasons:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Lack of discoverability: Data science artifacts are often spread across
 different locations and systems, making it difficult to find and access
 them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Lack of standardization: There is often a lack of standardization in terms
 of naming, formatting, and documentation of artifacts, which can make them
 difficult to understand and use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Lack of compatibility: Artifacts may be designed to work with specific versions
 of software or specific hardware configurations, making them difficult
 to use in other contexts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to this, we encounter the 
\series bold
reuse problem
\series default
, which is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center

\emph on
'Given a set of artifacts that are materialized, decide whether to compute
 or reuse them when executing a workflow, in order to obtain the smallest
 possible cost and constrained to budget and computing capabilities'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need to consider how costly it is to recompute the artifacts and how
 costly it is to reuse it, in terms of money or time.
 Note that the decision might vary when changing the metric used.
 This problem is computationally hard and is equivalent to the MaxFlow problem
 in graphs, taking 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(N^{3}\right)$
\end_inset

 time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Materialization refers to the process of creating an executable version
 of an artifact, usually in the form of a container or a compiled program,
 so that the artifact can be used in different environments.
 Materializing artifacts allows to make sure that the artifact runs in the
 same way regardless of the environment it runs on.
 Materialization of data science artifacts solves the problem of compatibility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are also difficulties of creating a materialized version of an artifact,
 which can be caused by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Complex dependencies: Data science artifacts often have complex dependencies,
 such as specific versions of software libraries or specific hardware configurat
ions.
 These dependencies can make it difficult to create a materialized version
 of the artifact that can be run in different environments.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Lack of automation: Creating a materialized version of an artifact can be
 a time-consuming and error-prone process, especially when done manually.
 Automation of the process is needed to make it efficient and reliable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve these issues, many organizations have started to implement data
 science platforms that can standardize the way artifacts are stored, shared,
 and reused, and also provide tools and frameworks for materializing artifacts.
 Additionally, using containerization and orchestration technologies like
 Docker and Kubernetes, provide a way to automate the process of materializing
 artifacts and make them more portable, which is an important aspect of
 the data science ecosystem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, we need to fight against the 
\series bold
materialization problem
\series default
 which states:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
'
\emph on
Given a prediction about future workflows, decide if and what artifacts
 to materialize'
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This problem is even harder: assuming complete knowledge of the future,
 the problem is still NP-hard...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Alternatives in Task-Artifacts graphs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the task-artifacts graphs, it is possible to find several paths to obtain
 the same artifact.
 So, we need to decide:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If we reuse an artifact or recompute it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Which path to follow to reach the artifact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this, we can use 
\series bold
AND/OR graphs
\series default
, which are an abstraction to represent alternatives in workflows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An 
\series bold
OR node
\series default
 means that there are alternative ways to reach the node, and only one incoming
 edge is necessary.
 All artifacts are OR nodes but most of them have only one alternative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An 
\series bold
AND node
\series default
 means that the node requires all incoming edges.
 All tasks are AND nodes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the optimal decision for each OR node is also a NP-hard problem.
\end_layout

